SIMPLE: possession
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Possession
<hw>Pos*ses"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>possession</ets>, L. <ets>possessio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act or state of possessing, or holding as one's own.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The having, holding, or detention
of property in one's power or command; actual seizin or occupancy;
ownership, whether rightful or wrongful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Possession may be either actual or constructive; actual,
when a party has the immediate occupancy; constructive, when he has only
the right to such occupancy.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The thing possessed; that which any one occupies,
owns, or controls; in the plural, property in the aggregate; wealth;
dominion; <as>as, foreign <ex>possessions</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the young man heard that saying, he went away sorrowful, for
he had great <qex>possessions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xix.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ananias, with Sapphira his wife, sold a <qex>possession</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts v. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The house of Jacob shall possess their <qex>possessions</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ob. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The state of being possessed or controlled, as by an
evil spirit, or violent passions; madness; frenzy; <as>as, demoniacal
<ex>possession</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How long hath this <qex>possession</qex> held the man?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To give possession</b></col>, <cd>to put in another's
power or occupancy.</cd> -- <col><b>To put in possession</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To invest with ownership or occupancy; to provide or
furnish with; as, <xex>to put</xex> one <xex>in possession</xex> of
facts or information</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>To place
one in charge of property recovered in ejectment or writ of entry.</cd>
-- <col><b>To take possession</b></col>, <cd>to enter upon, or to bring
within one's power or occupancy.</cd> -- <col><b>Writ of
possession</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a precept directing a sheriff
to put a person in peaceable possession of property recovered in
ejectment or writ of entry.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Possession</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Possession
<hw>Pos*ses"sion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To invest with
property.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Possessionary</ent>⟦br⟧
